Ireland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONIST and nationalist leaders succeeded yesterday in persuading the
government to hold a rare Commons' debate on Northern Ireland next Thursday
as part of efforts to encourage political dialogue in the province, Ralph
Atkins writes.
Mr James Molyneaux and the Rev Ian Paisley, the two Unionist leaders, and Mr
John Hume, of the nationalist Social Democratic and Labour party, agreed to
ask for the debate jointly at a private meeting at Westminster.
They are to meet again today in Belfast to discuss how obstacles to formal
political negotiations can be overcome. Mr Molyneaux said the three leaders
were 'endeavouring diligently' to fulfil a call by Mr John Major for them to
find a way of restarting talks. There is no signs yet that any progress has
been made, however.
Northern Ireland debates are usually related to specific motions - for
instance on anti-terrorism measures or renewing powers for 'direct rule'.
