FT  28 FEB 92 / Heseltine move to boost rural jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RURAL job creation schemes and new guidance on planning for rural
development were part of an Action for the Countryside package launched by
the government yesterday.
Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, said the package demonstrated a
new co-ordinated government approach to conservation and development. 'There
has to be development if our countryside is to survive in good heart into
the next century,' he said.
The package is a joint initiative by the environment department, the
agriculture ministry and three countryside organisations. Much of it is a
reshaping of existing schemes and finance, but Mr Heseltine said Pounds
31.5m of new money would be allocated over the next three years.
Schemes to boost rural economies will be run through the Rural Development
Commission. More money is to go into grants for the conversion of redundant
buildings in agricultural areas into tourist accommodation or shops.
Mr Heseltine said the government remained committed to strict planning
control in green belts. But it would promote a shift in emphasis from
retaining farmland to developing rural economies while protecting landscapes
and wildlife habitats.
