FT  28 FEB 92 / Scotland's recession shallower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION in Scotland is less severe than in the UK as a whole but
recovery north of the border is likely to be weaker, according to economists
from the Scottish Office writing in the latest Scottish Economic Bulletin.
Surveys of business and consumer confidence in the autumn and the fall in
unemployment for two successive months in that period, are cited as evidence
of the shallowness of the recession compared with the UK as a whole. This is
reinforced by evidence from production and construction indices to date,
showing the recession to be less severe than that of 1979-81.
Although the Scottish economy grew faster than that of the UK as a whole
between 1988 and last year, recovery will be weaker this year.
Job losses are likely to be lower in Scotland this year, but forecasters
expect sluggish employment growth in the medium term.
Scottish Economic Bulletin No 44 Winter 1991. HMSO. Pounds 11.50.
