FT  28 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): First Tec trainee charter announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BIRMINGHAM Training and Enterprise Council will be the first of the 82 Tecs
in England and Wales to introduce a trainee charter. This will set out the
rights and obligations of those taking part in training programmes.
Organisations providing such programmes for the Birmingham Tec will find
that agreement to observe the charter is a contractual requirement, a Tec
official explained yesterday.
Drawing up the charter, the text of which is circulating in Birmingham
training circles, is part of a general effort to raise training standards in
the city.
It is also a response to specific complaints from trainees about standards.
This, last year, led Birmingham Tec to cancel contracts with Acafess and
Cobalt UK, two local training companies.
The text of the charter to be introduced by Birmingham explains that it has
been drawn up after talks with trainees.
It specifies that each trainee should have a personal training plan agreed
with the training organisation.
The charter sets out the right to continuous assessment and states that
details of the trainees' hours of work, holidays and payments should be
given in writing.
It makes clear that the training should be undertaken 'by experienced and
qualified staff' in 'a safe and properly equipped training and working
environment'.
In return the trainee, under the terms of the charter, agrees to regular
attendance and good timing and accepts the obligation to notify the training
organisation in advance of any absence, including that for job interviews.
The trainee is expected to show 'responsible behaviour'.
A complaints procedure is also built into the charter. First, a trainee
should take up any grievance with the training organisation.
If this is not met the trainee is advised to contact the Birmingham Tec.
</TEXT>
