<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (1): A swathe through the investment
jungle - Foreword
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS HAVE a tough battle when dealing with the financial services
sector.
All too often they are offered products that they do not understand by
people whose motives they have every right to suspect. It is often hard to
tell whether the investment on offer is designed to boost the wealth of the
consumer, or to line the pocket of the salesmen.
A classic example is the way in which consumers are sold life
assurance-based savings products, which may offer good value if held for 15
or 25 years but are highly inflexible. A Securities and Investments Board
study found that up to 45 per cent of such policies are abandoned in the
first two years, with resulting abysmal returns to the policyholder.
One reason why so many of these policies are sold is that they bring
substantial commission to salesmen. Even someone who is called an
'independent' financial adviser is not necessarily unbiased; he or she has a
natural incentive to recommend those products which pay the highest
commission.
In such circumstances, newspapers are often seen as a crucial source of
independent information for the saver. But it is impossible, in the space
available to a daily newspaper, to cover all the topics in which a financial
consumer may be interested. Inevitably, a reader must take pot luck each
week on whether his own field is covered.
This A-Z is designed to help fill that gap. Within these pages, there should
be several articles which will appeal to every consumer.
The jargon of the financial services world - from annuities to zero-coupon
shares - is explained. But as well as specialist topics, there are articles
of a more general interest. For example, how are the banks and building
societies competing against each other to attract customers? How can a
husband and wife most efficiently organise their finances? What is the
current state of the mortgage market?
As you work your way through the guide, you should find that one subject
will lead to another. Those who turn to F for fixed rate investments might
be intrigued to know more about G for gilts. Anyone who reads L for life
insurance may find their thoughts drifting to the issue of wills and
inheritance tax (a subject duly covered under W).
As befits what we know of Financial Times readers, there is a strong focus
on equity investments. We include a guide to the art of picking 'cheap'
shares, known in the jargon as value investing. Other articles focus on
yields, dividends, and unit and investment trusts.
Of course, even this guide cannot be comprehensive, but we hope it will be a
useful work of reference and information for the saver and investor.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
