<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (2): A bet on how long you'll live -
Annuities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WE START with the investment you usually make at the end of your career.
An annuity is one of the most disarmingly simple products offered by the
financial services industry, yet a series of distressing issues must be
faced when you buy one.
You pay a lump sum to a life insurance company, or friendly society, which
then guarantees to pay you a (normally fixed) annual income for the rest of
your life. The money is invested in gilts (see G for Gilts) to ensure that
there is no risk with the repayments.
The life office will not pay you any more than the fixed sum, unless you buy
a specialised contract, and all payments cease when you die. Your heirs will
not benefit.
So when you buy an annuity you are effectively placing a bet on how long you
will live. If you die soon afterwards, the annuity will turn out to have
been a bad investment. But if you live to be 100, the annuity effectively
spreads your life savings to keep you financially secure in a lengthy
retirement.
Two chief factors affect annuity rates: the gilts market and life
expectancy. The higher the yield on gilts when you buy your annuity, the
better the annuity rate will be. More important, the annuity rate will be
higher if your life expectancy is shorter. This means that, as a general
rule, you should wait as long as possible before buying an annuity.
There are three different times in life when you might want to buy an
annuity.
When you retire: The bulk of the proceeds of a personal or self-employed
pension plan must, by law, be put into an annuity when you retire; as must
all the money you have saved through making additional voluntary
contributions to a corporate pension scheme. If your company pension scheme
operates in terms of a fraction of your final salary, then you will not have
the opportunity to buy an annuity with these funds. However, if the company
has a 'money purchase' scheme, you need to buy an annuity (see R for
Retirement Planning).
These annuities are referred to as 'compulsory purchase'. You pay income tax
on the entire annuity payment, as it is assumed that this will be your prime
source of income.
An easy way to boost your annuity payment is to use the 'open market
option'. This allows you to shop around different insurers for the best
rate, rather than just take the annuity offered by the company which managed
your pension fund. To do this, you need an independent financial adviser,
who can find the best rate on offer on the market.
For example, best rates last month all came from Sun Alliance, according to
Baronworth Investment Services. For a down-payment of Pounds 100,000, best
fixed rates available were Pounds 12,778 for a 60-year-old man, and Pounds
14,149 for a 65-year-old. A 55-year-old woman could receive a best rate of
Pounds 10,796, while a 60-year-old woman would receive Pounds 11,479.
Inflation is the great enemy of your income when you retire. If you are
lucky enough to have a long retirement, the real spending power of your
fixed-rate annuity may be eroded.
A range of annuities can combat this problem, but they are expensive.
Insurance companies usually offer protection against inflation only in
return for paying you a substantially lower annuity in the early years. The
longer you think you are likely to live, the more appropriate an
inflation-proofed annuity will be.
Annuity contracts which afford some protection against price rises are:
Index-linked annuities which rise in line with the retail prices index;
Increasing annuities which rise by a fixed amount each year (normally 5 per
cent);
With-profits annuities which add on a bonus, provided investment performance
can sustain one, each year; and
Unit-linked annuities which have the disadvantage that they can go down, but
should in the long run provide a haven against inflation.
A final option to consider is an underwritten annuity. These make most sense
if you have strong reason to believe that you do not have long to live. For
example, if you already have a history of heart trouble it could be
possible, with medical evidence, to persuade a life office to give you a
bigger annuity.
Figures from Sun Life show how much difference underwriting can make. A
65-year-old man could normally buy an annuity of Pounds 11,953 with a fund
of Pounds 100,000.
If he had twice suffered coronary thrombosis, most recently two years ago,
Sun Life would be prepared to pay an annuity of Pounds 14,427.72. If the man
were still exhibiting moderately raised blood pressure, the annuity would be
Pounds 15,123.24.
Once your decision is made, you are stuck with it, so give your pension
annuity a lot of thought.
When you need to increase your income in retirement. If you need extra funds
to pay for medical care in your home, or in a residential home, an annuity
may be the best way to do it. As people who do this are normally much older
than when they retired, the annuity rates available are more generous.
The tax regime is also more generous. When buying an 'immediate' annuity, as
such annuities are called, you pay tax only on the income element of the
payments - the portion of the annuity which is counted as repayment of
capital is tax-free.
According to Baronworth, best rates last month, for a Pounds 100,000 lump
sum, were: for 75-year-olds, Pounds 17,825 for men and Pounds 15,287 for
women, from Co-operative; and for 80-year-olds, Pounds 21,488 for men and
Pounds 20,078 for women, from Standard Life.
You can also buy an annuity that is 'capital-protected'. Thus, if you are
nervous about your heirs, you can opt for a contract which guarantees to
repay the capital to your estate if you die within a certain period. The
insurance company will keep any investment profits.
As people live longer and medical care improves, it is becoming more common
to buy annuities late in retirement. A popular route involves mortgaging a
part or all of your house, and buying an annuity with the proceeds. For
people much over the age of 75, the annuity payment should outstrip the
mortgage repayment costs, but take professional advice before doing this.
When you are putting together a complex financial package. For this purpose
you will usually need a temporary annuity. These differ from other annuities
in that they pay out over a fixed term, and then stop. This makes them very
useful as income providers when placed 'back-to-back' with another
investment which provides growth.
Typical plans might involve buying a temporary annuity for 10 years, and
putting another lump sum into a with-profits bond, or a personal equity
plan. The annuity would provide a substantial income, while the growth
investment would grow enough to replace the money spent on the annuity after
10 years. The end result, if the plan works, is that you have enjoyed high
income for 10 years with no loss of capital.
Temporary annuities are also popular as an aid to school-fees planning.
Parents save up a lump sum until their child starts at senior school, for
example, and then buy a temporary annuity for six years. This pays the fees
at the beginning of each educational year.
Baronworth's best buys last month on temporary nine-year annuities, for a
Pounds 100,000 lump sum, were: for 40-year-olds, Pounds 16,710 for men and
Pounds 16,730 for women, from Sun Alliance; and for 80-year-olds (possibly
of use for long-term care), Pounds 23,300 for men, from Standard Life, and
Pounds 20,170 for women, from Sun Alliance.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
