<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (23): It's cheap but is it a
bargain? - Value investing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CENTRAL principle of value investing is almost exactly 400 years old.
The secret of getting rich, wrote Thomas Lodge in 1595, is 'Buy cheape, sell
deare'. Value investing is the systematisation of that motto.
It is a disciplined, methodical approach to assessing when any particular
share is cheap and when it is expensive, rather than trying to judge whether
the stock market as a whole is over- or under-valued.
The phrase 'value investing' is an American one, and so is the best-known
treatise on the subject, Benjamin Graham and David Dodd's book Security
Analysis, published in 1934. The authors set out a detailed set of rules for
assessing stocks against their intrinsic value. This was based on weighing
up a company's assets, calculating its future earning power, and deriving a
price to which the market was likely to gravitate over time, based on an
appropriate price/earnings ratio.
In Graham and Dodd's slightly ponderous prose: 'It is our thesis that the
stocks of companies with disappointing earnings usually sell lower than they
should, for the same basic reason that stocks as a whole sell too low during
periods of depression. The significance of the unfavourable conditions is
exaggerated.'
Since then, the basic techniques of value investing have not changed: find
cheap stocks and hold them - perhaps for a long time - until their intrinsic
value is recognised by the market. Since the 1930s, however, it has become
much harder to find shares that are grossly undervalued. And since then,
professional value investors have acquired computers, allowing them to
search rapidly through huge databases of corporate financial data. For the
private investor, similar effects can be achieved, more laboriously but much
more cheaply, by poring over the FT's share price listings.
If in late January you had asked the FT Analysis computer database for all
big UK companies selling at a discount to net asset value which also had a
modest price/earnings ratio and a healthy dividend yield, you would have
come up with a handful of answers. These include Asda, the stores group,
trading at a p/e ratio of 8 and a yield of 8 per cent; British Aerospace
(p/e of 3, yield of 12 per cent); British Steel (no earnings, but a historic
yield of 15 per cent); and Trafalgar House, (p/e of 10, yield of 19 per
cent), the shipping and construction group.
All of these have fallen out of favour with the stock market, often because
of problems suffered by the industries in which they do the bulk of their
business. Only more detailed analysis would suggest if all these companies
deserve their current cheapness.
How do you tell when a share is offering true value? The latest annual
report will give you useful information: the strength of the company's
balance sheet, the businesses from which it derives the bulk of its profits,
and its long-term record of growth in earnings and dividends. The detailed
FT-Actuaries All-Share indices, published in the FT every day, will give you
a sense of the typical p/e ratio for companies in that sector (in the case
of Asda, for example, food chains were selling at a 15 p/e ratio).
A word of warning: the reason why stocks are on high yields and low p/e
ratios is that the market perceives them to be risky. These perceptions
could be right. As a result, most value investors buy a spread of stocks,
hoping that the recovery of some will outweigh the losses on a few. Private
investors should beware of putting too much of their portfolio in one or two
risky stocks.
Just how risky apparently 'cheap' stocks can be is shown by three other
companies that were also thrown up by that database search: Polly Peck,
Maxwell Communication Corporation, and British and Commonwealth. All three
are currently in administration, with little prospect of a return for
shareholders. Yet by the crude yardstick used for the database search, they
looked cheap. Moral: cheapness is not the same as good value.
There is one other trap. When the market is selling at historically high
price/earnings multiples - as Wall Street has been doing recently  - there
is a risk of picking up stocks which are relatively cheap but absolutely
dear. Graham and Dodd put it neatly: 'Beware of 'bargains' when most stocks
seem very high', they wrote - and it's as true now as it was in 1934.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXI Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-6366</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAAXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (24): Don't leave your heir on a
shoestring - Wills &amp; inheritance tax
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
YOU MAY hate the idea of writing a will. But if you do not, the state will
write it for you. And you may not like what it says. British intestacy rules
may be fine by you, but you should check.
English, Scottish and Northern Irish law vary on the precise arrangements if
you die without writing a will. In England, if you leave a spouse behind
you, they will receive your entire estate if it is less than Pounds 75,000.
If it comes to more than this, things get baffling.
If you have no children, your spouse receives the house, its contents and
any personal effects. After that, the spouse will receive the first Pounds
125,000 of the estate, and then half of the residue beyond this. If you have
surviving direct relatives - parents, brothers and sisters  - then the
remainder is shared between them. If you have children, the spouse only
receives Pounds 75,000, plus a life interest in half of the residue. The
other half of the residue is split between the children, once they reach the
age of 18.
If these rules do not suit you, call a solicitor and write a will.
This is only the first step towards guaranteeing your heirs a healthy
inheritance. If you are wealthy, it may pay to enter the labyrinthine world
of estate planning.
The future for inheritance tax (IHT) is more uncertain than for any other
form of taxation. Conservatives have hinted that the Budget will see radical
reform, possibly the doubling of the threshold before tax is payable.
A Labour government would make similarly radical changes, in the opposite
direction. It wants to change IHT into a recipient-based tax, related to the
amount received by individuals, rather than the total amount eft in the
estate - thus encouraging people to distribute wealth more widely in their
wills.
While politicians are making up their minds, it is best to look at the
current regime and work from there. The main points to bear in mind are:
There is a threshold of Pounds 140,000 before any IHT is payable. Amounts
above this level are taxed at a single tax rate of 40 per cent.
Money left to a spouse is tax-free. The Pounds 140,000 threshold can be
given in addition to this exempt bequest.
You can make a gift of up to Pounds 3,000 each year, exempt from all IHT in
addition to all other reliefs. You can carry forward unused exemption for
one year, but you must use up all of your current year's exemption before
using any exemption carried forward.
'Small gifts' of up to Pounds 250 can be made to any number of individuals
in a year without affecting your overall allowance for the year. Thus, if
you gave the maximum to 12 people you would have given away Pounds 3,000,
without eating into the additional Pounds 3,000 annual exemption.
Regular gifts out of income, which can be proved to the Revenue not to
affect seriously your standard of living, are exempt.
Bequests to charities, political parties and various other non-profit-making
organisations are exempt.
Gifts to individuals or to various trusts can be exempt, if they are made
more than seven years before death. These are 'potentially exempt
transfers', because they lose some, or possibly all, of their exemption if
the donor dies within seven years of making the gift. Tax on gifts of above
the threshold allowance is subject to 'tapering relief' - the longer the
donor survives, the less tax will be applied. There are so many loopholes
here that some accountants call IHT a 'voluntary tax'. How you go about
minimising it depends on how much you are prepared to give away.
The three main weapons at your disposal are trusts, whole-of-life policies,
and back-to-back schemes. All have advantages, but carry costs:
Whole-of-life policies are best if you do not want to give anything away. A
couple can take out a joint whole-of-life policy with a sum assured, equal
to the amount they expect to have to pay in inheritance tax on the estate.
When the second parent dies, this policy automatically pays the children's
inheritance tax for them (see also L for life assurance).
Life policies for the elderly are not cheap - a couple in their late fifties
could expect to pay annual premiums of around Pounds 7,000 to cover a
liability of Pounds 250,000. You should also beware of high commissions and
costs. But the approach has the benefit of simplicity.
Trusts are subtler, and potentially more useful, if more expensive. They
come in bewildering varieties, but the basic idea is that money gifted to a
trust, over which you may be able to exert a certain level of control, can
count as having left your estate for IHT purposes, provided you cannot
benefit from the money yourself.
A typical IHT plan buys an insurance bond and puts it in trust. You can also
use an insurance bond as a package for an existing portfolio, which will be
preferable in many cases.
Back-to-back policies are commission-rich. You buy an annuity, automatically
slashing the value of your estate. You then use the annuity both for income,
and to fund (you guessed it) a whole-of-life policy. This pays out to your
heirs, when their IHT liability has already been slashed by the annuity.
Take advice from solicitors, accountants or other fee-charging advisers
before taking any action. This is a deeply emotive topic, and you should not
be rushed into doing anything you do not want to do.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXI Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-6367</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAAWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (10): A good deal even if RPI should
fall - Inflation-proofing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
INFLATION IS the great enemy of savers. Even an annual rate of 5 per cent,
modest by modern standards, halves the value of money in 15 years.
A generation of German savers was ruined by hyperinflation in the 1920s, and
British savers had a pretty rough time of it in the 1970s.
In the 1980s, by contrast, high real interest rates, lower direct taxes and
lower inflation helped savers to prosper. But this prosperity may have
lowered savers' defences. It has been simple and secure to deposit one's
cash in the building societies and enjoy the interest.
It is difficult to imagine the same conditions prevailing through the 1990s.
There will not be much UK economic growth if base rates remain at 10.5 per
cent and inflation at 4.5 per cent - a real rate of 6 per cent. According to
Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the historic average for real returns on gilts
(1919-91) is 1.2 per cent and for Treasury bills (1946-91) 0.5 per cent. The
likelihood is, therefore, that either inflation will rise, or interest rates
will fall, to narrow the current gap.
In either case, savers will suffer. The nominal value of their income may
fall; the real value certainly will.
Index-linked investments offer security against these dangers. There are two
main types: gilt and National Savings (see letters G and N). Each guarantees
to keep pace with inflation, with a cushion on top.
The gilts are the more complex of the two. They will be repaid at a level
that depends on the increase in the retail price index between the issue and
maturity. So if the RPI on issue is 100, and at maturity is 200, the gilt
will be repaid at double its issue price.
That sounds simple enough. Complications start with the fact that the gilts
also pay a small income, 2 to 2 1/2 per cent, which is also index-linked.
The second complexity is that the actual RPIs used for indexation purposes
are the ones eight months before issue and maturity. This means that the
buyer is at risk from inflation in the last eight months of the life of the
gilt.
The result of this is that, when one buys an index-linked gilt, one cannot
be sure of the nominal, or even the real, return to redemption. The
convention is to quote the real yield on two assumptions - 5 and 10 per cent
inflation.
In late January, the real yield on the longest dated gilt (which matures in
2024) would have been 4.2 per cent (if inflation till maturity averages 5
per cent) and 4.1 per cent (if inflation is 10 per cent).
These real yields are very attractive in historical terms, especially since
the bulk of the return will come in the form of tax-free capital gains.
If one expects inflation to be 5 per cent, then the long-term nominal return
on index-linked would be 9.2 per cent. That translates to around 8.7 per
cent net for the basic rate taxpayer and 8 per cent net for those on the top
rate. For a building society to match these net returns, it would have to
offer gross returns of around 11.6 and 13.3 per cent respectively. The
former level might be available in the short term, but would be highly
unlikely over the longer term.
Equities (see letter E) are often touted as a hedge against inflation; and
indeed, over the long term, BZW figures show they have produced gross real
returns well in excess of those currently available from index-linked gilts.
There are snags, however. The first is tax. BZW shows that the real return
on equities between 1960 and 1991 has been 5.3 per cent per annum, with
gross income reinvested; but for the investor on the top rate of tax, the
real return has been just 1.2 per cent. Admittedly, top tax rates were very
high during part of that period.
The second snag is that the BZW figures are based on the equity indices, and
there is no guarantee that the portfolios of private investors will match
those indices.
So index-linked gilts could offer a very attractive long-term alternative to
equities for private investors, especially those who pay top rate tax.
A shorter-term alternative is index-linked National Savings. The current
issue of certificates offers a return of inflation plus 4.5 per cent
tax-free, if held for five years (the returns are significantly lower if
cashed in early).
Again, this return is highly attractive. Those who bought an earlier issue
of these certificates in January 1987 would have achieved a return of 64.6
per cent. That beat the average unit and investment trust, and a top-rate
building society account, over the same period.
The disadvantage with these certificates is that they do not provide any
income. The low coupon on the index-linked gilts is also a problem for
income-seeking investors.
But do not dismiss index-linked investment just because you think inflation
is going to fall. If you do believe in the depressed, low-inflation 1990s,
just look at the US. Thanks to attempts to revive the economy, US savers are
receiving rates of only 4 per cent. Even if US inflation were expected to
average 2 per cent, a real yield of 4.5 per cent would be pretty attractive
to them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
