<DOCNO>FT921-6372</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAARFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (20): Mind the tax trap if you take
income - Single-premium bonds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SINGLE-premium bond is the life industry's answer to the unit trust  -
with a small amount of life assurance as the icing on the cake.
Each insurance company selling investment bonds sets its own minimum for the
level of one-off lump sum or single premium to be accepted, generally in a
range from Pounds 250 to Pounds 2,500. Charges are similar to those for unit
trusts - an initial 5 per cent plus an annual 1 per cent for management.
Investment bonds come in three main varieties:
With-profits bonds: Last year, investors took a 'safety-first' attitude and
poured into with-profits bonds, which add on non-reversible bonuses each
year, in a manner similar to with-profits endowments. For example, Norwich
Union took Pounds 700m into its with-profits bond, three times the 1990
total, straining its liquidity and threatening future pay-outs to
policyholders.
The company reacted by pulling down the shutters on future business in the
bonds from independent financial advisers, or brokers - in effect a 95 per
cent cutback, although NU's tied agents are still allowed to sell the bonds.
Unit-linked bonds allow investment in a selection of specialised funds
holding gilts, international equities, money-market instruments or property.
They offer the facility to switch between funds without incurring entry
charges - an advantage over unit trusts. Decisions about switching among the
funds may be taken by the investors themselves or turned over to the
insurance company or to a broker for a fee.
This led to 'broker bonds', carrying the name of the broker making the
investment decisions rather than the insurance company holding the money.
These were investigated by the Securities and Investments Board, which at
first seemed intent on a total ban but then settled for imposing tighter
regulations.
Unit-linked bonds are commission-heavy. Investors choosing between unit
trusts and bonds should realise that, on a Pounds 10,000 investment, this is
eqivalent to choosing between an investment paying Pounds 300 in commission
(unit trusts) and one paying possibly Pounds 600 (bonds).
You are unlikely to be told this. Instead, arguments presented to investors
emphasise features such as tax treatment and the costs of switching
underlying investments, often ignoring a potentially damaging tax trap.
Guaranteed income bonds provide a fixed rate of return for a set number of
years, paying back the original capital at the end of the term.
A guaranteed growth bond will repay the original capital after a set term
plus a specified return on the capital - for example, matching any increase
in the FTSE-100 index. But guarantees are always paid for by the investor.
Such a guarantee is only a pledge to follow the changes in share prices,
taking no account of dividends, which will be pocketed by the insurance
company.
Interest rate levels have also boosted sales of guaranteed income bonds,
with 10 per cent seen as the 'magic' rate, sure to attract large numbers of
investors.
Brokers are increasingly competing on guaranteed bond rates by using the
commission they receive to augment the rate offered by the insurance
company. They have plenty of scope to do so. Commission on a Pounds 10,000
guaranteed-income bond could be up to Pounds 150, while some brokers
estimate that selling a bond on an 'execution only' basis, without advising
an investor costs only about Pounds 10 in form-filling time.
The tax position: A basic-rate taxpayer has no income or capital gains taxes
to pay on part or complete withdrawals from a bond.
Higher-rate taxpayers may be charged 15 per cent tax (the difference between
the 40 per cent higher rate and 25 per cent) when a with-profits or
unit-linked bond is fully surrendered or cashed in on the death of the
holder - the charge would be only on the part of the proceeds exceeding the
original premium.
But, thanks to the rules on partial withdrawals, even millionaires can
remove themselves from the higher-rate tax bracket with the help of
investment bonds. Investors can withdraw up to 5 per cent a year of the
amount originally invested without having to pay higher-rate tax. This can
continue for up to 20 years, when all of the original value has been used
up.
Although higher-rate tax is due when the bond is finally cashed in,
investors are able to claim top-slicing relief on any profit they have made.
This works by averaging the profit over the number of years the bond has
been in place and adding the result to the investor's income, to arrive at
any higher rate tax due. For example, a profit of Pounds 10,000 on a bond
fully cashed in 10 years after the original investment, amounts to an
average profit of Pounds 1,000 to be added to the investor's income for that
final year. The higher-rate tax figure arrived at in this way would be
multiplied by 10 to produce the tax bill.
The serious catch with investment bonds is that investors who exceed the 5
per cent annual withdrawal can find themselves paying 15 per cent tax on a
gain when their bond is showing a loss.
An investor who put Pounds 20,000 into a bond before October 1987 could have
been left with units worth considerably less three years later. Under the 5
per cent rule, he would have been able to withdraw up to 15 per cent, or
Pounds 3,000, from the bond without any immediate tax penalty. But a
withdrawal of Pounds 10,000 would land him with a bill for 15 per cent
(Pounds 1,050) on his Pounds 7,000 'gain'. Theoretically the tax treatment
would even out in succeeding years, though this seems unlikely, given the
dent made in the investment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-6373</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAAQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (6): An inflation hedge if you buy
wisely - Equities
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
EQUITIES ARE the siren voice of the investment market. Private investors are
conscious of the allure; everyone knows someone who has made a killing,
either on a privatisation or a small company stock.
But many investors are also aware of the rocks on which the sirens sit. The
recent corporate collapses of Maxwell and Polly Peck have illustrated how
quickly the value of equity investments can evaporate.
Fear is normally stronger than greed. All too often, a roaring bull market
is required before investors can be persuaded to leave the safety of their
building society for the excitement of equities. Of course, they then buy at
exactly the wrong moment, and are then disillusioned for another decade when
share prices inevitably fall.
The danger with keeping money for long periods in the building society is of
a fall in the real (after inflation) rather than the nominal value of
capital. Over the period 1946-91, figures from Barclays de Zoete Wedd show
that the average* annual real return on equities was 6.14 per cent; the real
return on Treasury bills (a rough equivalent to building society returns)
over the same period was just 0.53 per cent per year.
From these figures, equities seem to be the obvious inflation hedge, but
there are snags. BZW's indices do not reflect costs and, of course, there is
no guarantee that the stocks selected by private investors will match the
performance of the indices.
At the moment, the risk and tax-free returns provided by National Savings (a
real 4.5 per cent if held for five years) look very attractive compared with
BZW's figures for equities.
National Savings (see letter N) do not provide income, however, and
investors should not forget the ability of shares to pay a rising income in
the form of dividends. BZW's equity income index show that dividends
increased almost tenfold in nominal terms between 1970 and 1991, and rose 40
per cent in real terms over the same period.
So there is a strong long-term case for investing in equities. What strategy
ought you to follow? To get a properly diversified portfolio of individual
shares, you probably need to invest around Pounds 50,000. For most small
investors, the risk of picking the wrong stocks is so high that it is best
for them to gain access to equities via the vehicle of a unit or investment
trust (see letter U).
Those who have enough money to invest directly in shares will still probably
need the advice and help of a stockbroker. The difficulty of finding the
right broker is what dissuades many people from investing in shares. Brokers
have a snooty image, and the man in the street often assumes that his meagre
portfolio will not be worthy of attention.
In fact, after some rather lean years for their industry, brokers are a lot
more welcoming than they used to be.
What sort of broker you need depends on how much you know about the market.
If you haven't a clue about shares, then you probably need the services of a
discretionary broker. He or she will manage the portfolio on your behalf,
and sort out such matters as the collection of dividends and the efficient
use of your capital gains tax allowance.
These days, such brokers will often charge a fee, based on the size of your
portfolio. They have therefore every incentive to see that your investments
perform, because their fee will rise in proportion.
An advisory, or dealing-only, broker will be more suitable for those who
know their way round the stock market and which stocks to select. Such
brokers may be available for a quick chat on the lines of 'what do you think
of ICI shares?' but mainly they will leave the decisions up to you.
They will be paid in terms of commission on each trade they make on your
behalf, and the rates they charge will be one of the most important factors
in your choice. Small investors should particularly look for the minimum
commission per deal.
A directory of brokers can be obtained by writing to the Stock Exchange in
London. Alternatively, there is a full list in the back of Beginners' Guide
to Investment, by Bernard Gray, published by Business Books Limited at
Pounds 8.95, which also contains a lot of useful information on owning
shares.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII Illustration (Omitted). Graph (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
