<DOCNO>FT921-6375</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAANFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (22): Two routes that help to cut
the risk - Unit and investment trusts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECENT corporate collapses of Polly Peck and Maxwell Communications have
illustrated the risks of share-picking for small investors.
One way to reduce those risks is to buy into unit or investment trusts. Each
invests in a wide portfolio of shares, so that even a collapse such as
Maxwell's will have only a small effect on the overall value of the fund.
Their different names reflect different structures. Unit trusts are what is
called open-ended funds, which means that the fund can increase or decrease
in size depending on investor demand. If the fund is worth Pounds 100m and
investors buy another Pounds 10m worth of units, then the fund manager will
have to buy a further Pounds 10m of shares to increase the size of the
portfolio to Pounds 110m. If sales of Pounds 20m are then made, the manager
will have to sell Pounds 20m worth of shares.
As a consequence, the value of the units is always directly related to the
value of the fund. If the fund is worth Pounds 100m, and there are 100m
units, then each unit should be worth 100p (ignoring, for the moment, the
bid-offer spread).
Investment trusts, in contrast, are closed-end funds. They are companies
quoted on the stock exchange with a set number of shares, which is rarely
changed. Investors buy and sell the shares from each other, instead of, in
the case of unit trusts, directly from the manager.
The price of investment trust shares, while broadly related to the value of
the portfolio, is also governed by supply and demand. If more investors want
to sell than buy shares, the share price will fall, regardless of whether or
not the value of the portfolio has fallen.
It is thus unlikely that the share price of an investment trust with Pounds
100m of assets and 100m shares would be exactly 100p. Normally, the trust's
shares would stand at a discount to asset value at, say, 90p.
This factor creates an extra risk for those who back investment trusts. If
they buy when the discount is narrow and it then widens, they will have lost
money, even if the value of the portfolio is unchanged. Of course, the
opposite is true; if the discount narrows, then the investor gains, even if
the value of the portfolio has not risen.
A narrowing of discounts has occurred over the last few years, with the
result that the performance of investment trusts has been far better than
that of their unit trust rivals. The average investment trust made a gain of
50.5 per cent over the five years to January 1, compared with a rise of just
30.1 per cent in the average unit trust.
Investment trusts have revived demand for their shares among private
investors, partly through monthly savings schemes, partly through ingenious
tax-efficient share structures, and partly through paying commissions to
intermediaries to sell them.
This last factor, in particular, has started to erode one of the perceived
advantages of investment trusts over unit trusts - their lower costs.
Typically, unit trust investors pay an initial charge of between 5 and 6 per
cent - of which around half normally goes to the salesman - and 1 to 1.5 per
cent in management fees.
Annual management fees on investment trusts tend to be below 1 per cent, and
the initial spread depends on the liquidity of the trust's shares. In
January, for example, the spread on shares in the largest trust, Foreign &amp;
Colonial, was just over 1 per cent; while the spread on the small Capital
Gearing trust was 10 per cent.
Lower costs have been another factor behind the outperformance of investment
trusts. But the cost structure of M&amp;G's Income Investment Trust, launched
last year, was almost bang in line with unit trust industry standards.
This factor, together with the proliferation of investment trust launches in
1991 and 1992, could mean that unit trusts will bounce back in the 1990s. If
investment trust managers swamp demand with new issues, discounts will
widen; and the share price performance will suffer.
But arguments about the relative merits of the two kinds of trust should not
blind investors to the very real advantages that each can offer.
Better-off private investors may be able to build up a UK share portfolio of
their own. But for most people, the only sensible way to get access to
overseas shares is via a unit or investment trust.
The industry has gone out of its way to provide for every conceivable
investor interest - from East Germany to Latin America, and from Spain to
New Zealand.
And via split-capital investment trusts, an investor can pick and choose the
nature of his investment - from shares that pay a high yield but incur a
capital loss, via zeros which offer no yield but steady capital growth, to
warrants which grant the investor a way of gambling on a sharp upward move
in the market.
All this is accessible, through a savings scheme, for as little as Pounds 25
a month, making unit and investment trusts the obvious starting point for
anyone interested in the stock market.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
HOW THEY DIFFER
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
UNIT TRUSTS                         INVESTMENT TRUSTS
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Not quoted on the stock market      Quoted on the stock market
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Investor buys units                 Investor buys shares
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Priced on asset value               Priced on supply and demand
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Number of units in issue rises      Number of shares in issue remains
and falls as investors buy and      constant
sell units
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Cannot borrow                       Can borrow
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Investor pays initial charge of     Investor pays brokers commission of
5-6 per cent, included in           1.5 to 2 per cent (less in savings
bid-offer spread                    scheme) plus 0.5 per cent stamp duty
                                    plus market buy-sell spread
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Annual management charge of 1       Annual management charge of 0.5 to
to 1.5 per cent                     0.75 per cent
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
