<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (12): VAT helps to rob gold of its
magic - Krugerrands
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
KRUGERRANDS HAVE not received any promotion or advertising support for seven
years. Yet there can be very few readers who do not recognise their name.
They are the coins launched by South Africa in 1967 to provide investors
with the opportunity to buy gold in small quantities. As the world's biggest
gold producer, South Africa had a vested interest in this attempt to turn
small investors into big 'gold bugs'.
During the following 18 years, Krugerrands dominated the gold coin market.
More than 44m troy ounces of gold was used to make them (about 1,400
tonnes), and sales spurted to a peak of more than 6m ounces, or 170 tonnes,
in 1978.
But demand had dropped to 1m ounces by 1985, the year sanctions were imposed
against South Africa by the US and the European Community.
Sanctions recently have been removed - the EC's as recently as January 28
this year - and the South Africans have been working on a detailed marketing
strategy to re-launch the Krugerrand. But they won't say when.
Their reluctance is understandable. Many private investors have lost all
interest in gold, and this is an exceptionally difficult time in the gold
coin market. Demand is at the lowest level for many years, and forecasts
suggest that the combined sales of the five best-selling coins last year
reached only about half the 2.4m ounces sold in 1990.
The position is even more disastrous in the UK, because since 1982 investors
have had to pay value added tax, currently 17.5 per cent, to take delivery
at home (this cannot be reclaimed when the gold is sold).
The imposition of VAT virtually killed off investment by private individuals
in physical gold in the UK, even though the tax can be avoided if the metal
is delivered offshore. Today, a UK private investor has tremendous
difficulty trying to find someone to deal with if gold bars or coins are on
the shopping list. All the big bullion houses have dropped out of the
business, and will only look after long-standing private customers.
There are other deterrents, apart from VAT, to investment in physical gold:
no interest is paid on the cash invested; there are storage and extra
insurance costs; there is a currency risk, because gold's price is
denominated in dollars. Gains on its price will often be offset by losses on
the dollar.
But the main reason gold has fallen out of favour with private investors is
that it simply has not lived up to its reputation of being 'a store of
value' over time. The price has been falling steadily for more than three
years. Over the past 10 years, gold has given up about 70 per cent of its
value in real terms.
Gold bought 10 years ago at Dollars 459.25 an ounce should now be valued at
Dollars 823 just to match an investment netting a modest compound 6 per cent
rate of interest. Last year gold's price averaged Dollars 362, and many
analysts suggest that it may manage Dollars 400 or thereabouts in 1992.
There are signs that the market's structure has changed. In the past 10
years, a host of gold-backed financial instruments, such as gold options,
has eroded the importance of the physical gold market and helped to curb the
price volatility which used to attract short-term speculators.
Moreover, the market is being dampened by the behaviour of the gold
producers themselves, who seem to have little faith that the price will
recover substantially. Every time the price rallies there is a rush by
producers to sell forward - that is, to fix future delivery at a determined
price and 'lock in' a profit.
Edwin Arnold, a vice-president and metals specialist at the Merrill Lynch
financial services group, says the vast bulk of private and institutional
money that would have gone into gold or gold futures 10 years ago now goes
into financial futures or derivative gold option products instead.
He adds: 'Gold is not some magical store of value. There is nothing mystical
about gold. It is really nothing more than a high-priced industrial metal.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-6378</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAAKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (26): A measure of value but also of
risk - Yield
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS vital for any investor who wants to buy shares or bonds to understand
the principle of yield. Put simply, the yield on an investment is the rate
of return that the investor can expect. It may come in the form of income
(interest or dividends) or capital growth.
Yield is calculated by dividing the return (in whatever form) by the price
of the investment returned. This leads to the golden rule that, as prices
rise, yields fall - and vice versa.
Consequently markets use yields as a measure of the value of shares and
bonds. If a share or bond has a higher than average yield, this may be a
sign that it is attractive; that the price is set to rise (and the yield to
fall).
On the other hand, a share or bond may be trading at a higher than average
yield because the market perceives it to be risky. Investors may fear that
dividends will not be paid, or interest payments met. The price of such a
bond or share falls to a point where the yield is deemed sufficiently
attractive to compensate investors for the higher risk.
Some believe that these higher-yielding shares and bonds offer rewards that
more than compensate investors for risk. In the US, the now imprisoned
Michael Milken, of Drexel Burnham, persuaded many investors to buy so-called
'junk bonds' with very high yields, which he argued would bring above-normal
returns.
In the UK, a number of fund managers have prospered by investing in
high-yielding equities. UK equity income unit trusts proved to be the second
best sector over 10 years to January 1 1992, with an average rise of 405.2
per cent. But the recession in the UK has caused many companies cash-flow
difficulties, and a number are considering cutting their dividend, a move
which would result in a fall in the share price. This would badly affect
equity income trusts.
Yield on bonds: The rate of return on a bond is not the same as its coupon -
the slip of paper which the investor presents for payment of the interest or
dividend on the due date - because the bond is bought at its prevailing
price and not at its redemption price. The yield on a bond can be calculated
in two ways:
Current yield: This measures the income that an investor receives from
holding a bond over the next year. The calculation involves dividing the
bond's coupon by its price and multiplying the result by 100 to obtain a
percentage.
Redemption yield: Also known as the yield-to-maturity, this is a more
accurate, but complicated, way of calculating the yield. It takes into
account the fact that, as well as earning interest, a capital gain or loss
may be made by owning a bond until its redemption date. The calculation is
made and published in the Financial Times tables of British funds (see G for
gilts).
Yield curve: Another important aspect of yields is the different returns on
offer for short- and long-term investments. These can be plotted on a graph
and shown as the 'yield curve'.
In the late 1980s, short-term interest rates were pushed to very high
levels, above the returns offered by gilts. This was, in the jargon, a
backward-sloping yield curve. But short-term rates have fallen, and the
yield curve has flattened. This means in practical terms that private
investors can earn returns on gilts that match, and sometimes beat, those
available from building societies.
Dividend yield: This is the measure of yield for shares, calculated by the
relationship of the gross dividend to the share price. It can be a very
useful way to decide the cheapness or expensiveness of shares in general.
The historical average dividend yield is 5 per cent. As a rule of thumb,
when the market yields substantially more than this, shares look cheap; when
they yield less, shares are relatively dear.
As an example, in the black days of 1974, yields rose to 12 per cent, just
before the great bull market; and in the summer of 1987, yields fell below 3
per cent, just before the crash.
Earnings yield: This is another way of examining the 'value' of share prices
(see V for value investing). It relates a company's profits to its share
price. In essence, it is the inverse of that oft-quoted measure of share
value, the price-earnings ratio: a share with a p/e ratio of 10 would have
an earnings yield of 1/10 - ie, 10 per cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXII Illustration (Omitted). Graph (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-6379</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CB1BLAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920228
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  28 FEB 92 / A-Z of Personal Finance (13): The choice is wide but value
varies - Life assurance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LIFE ASSURANCE is a misnomer. A more accurate description might be 'death
insurance'.
In its simplest form, family breadwinners buy an insurance policy, paying
premiums in the same way as for more general insurance. It protects
dependants from the financial consequences of losing their breadwinner.
But the life industry has sprawled beyond this, and now accounts for the
lion's share of Britain's long-term savings.
The reasons for this are historical. Unlike general insurance, life insurers
do not need to worry about 'moral hazard' - there is rarely much dispute
over whether someone has indeed died - and mortality tables allow them to
plan their commitments with a strong degree of certainty.
Thus, life funds were soon able to move into more ambitious investments.
They made profits. Then they started returning the profits to investors.
Hence the 'with-profits' policy.
So 'life insurance' now includes a number of products that are competitive
as investments, but do not offer good value life cover in themselves (see Q
for Qualifying endowment policy, and S for Single-premium investment bonds).
The remaining products in the life companies' arsenal make sense for those
who merely want to protect their families. They come in two variants:
Term assurance insures your life for a fixed period. If you die before that
period has elapsed, your family receives the pay-out. If you live out the
term, the company keeps all your premiums. (Endowments are conceptually
similar to term assurance, but guarantee a payment at the end of the term,
even if the policyholder has survived. They should not be regarded as
protection policies, but mainly as investments.)
Whole-of-life assurance, as its name implies, offers a pay-out throughout
your life. Even if you live to be 100, the insurance company will pay out
when you die.
Which of the two protection policies will make the most sense?
As ever with insurance, a lot depends on you. If you have cash-flow
difficulties at the time you first have children, it makes sense to go for
the cheapest option, even though this could work out more expensive in the
long run. If not, then it might be better to aim for the longer term.
But one principle is definite - use an independent broker, preferably one
who charges fees or at least splits commission. Different insurers choose to
aim for business from specific groups. Thus, the company with the 'best buy'
for a 29-year-old man may not provide the best value for a 39-year-old
woman. Some may make flexible versions of their contracts particularly
attractive.
So generalisations about which offices offer the best and worst value are
impossible. But if you go to a tied agent, you will be limited to one
company, which may not offer a competitive deal for someone like you. An
independent adviser can shop around for the best rate to suit your
requirements.
A lot depends on your attitude to undergoing a medical examination. Some
companies will set a maximum level for the cover you can receive without
submitting to a medical, although this is often very high - Pounds 200,000
or more. Other medical criteria can vary - smokers, for example, are
unlikely to get good value from a company which offers a discount to
non-smokers.
Much has been changed by Aids, which has smashed through many actuarial
assumptions on mortality rates. While the chance of a full-blown Aids
epidemic among the UK's younger population remains, life insurance deals
will probably remain more expensive, and less flexible, than they were.
Aids has effectively finished off some of the better-value ways to take out
cheap term assurance. However, term assurance is always the cheaper option.
When you have children, it is often good value to take out insurance on a
'joint life, first death' basis - in other words, it pays out after the
first partner of the couple dies.
The premiums for term assurance depend on your age when you start the
policy, and the length of the term - the older you are and the longer the
term, the more you pay.
You can thus save money by starting with a short term, such as five years.
This will be very cheap. But be warned. If, during the five years, you have
a heart attack or anything else which would show up on the standard
questionnaire and render you uninsurable, you would not be able to buy a
further term. Another term would, in any case, be more expensive, because
you would be older.
This leads to a number of complex contracts, which begin to merge term
assurance with whole-of-life:
Renewable term guarantees that you can re-insure yourself at the end of the
first term, even if you have fallen seriously ill in the meantime. You would
still have to pay a higher premium on the second term, based on your age.
Convertible term is the same, but also allows you to convert to a
whole-of-life policy, even if you have fallen ill.
Increasing term allows you to increase the amount of cover automatically
during the term.
You can short-circuit the problem of reinsuring yourself by buying a
whole-of-life policy. This also carries the benefit that you can receive a
'surrender value' - in other words, if you decide you do not want to
continue the policy at some point, you will receive some money back. Many
policies allow you to link a whole-of-life policy to a choice of funds.
Whole-of-life policies do not stand up as investments in their own right.
But the ability to derive a surrender value, once you have no dependants and
no need for life insurance, does go a long way towards justifying the extra
cost when you start the policy.
There can be no hard or fast rules - if you are strapped for cash, look at
one of the renewable or convertible term policies; or if you are confident
you can afford it, a whole-of-life policy. Whatever you do, go to a broker.
You might also want to look at a new breed of policies. Changing
demographics have forced life offices to offer protection against
contracting a serious illness and surviving it, or living into an
over-lengthy retirement. This has led to critical-illness and long-term care
policies (see H for health insurance). Some offer good value and others do
not.
But they have not rendered basic life protection obsolete. Term insurance is
cheaper than it was, and if you have children, or have taken out a mortgage,
it would be the gravest folly not to buy cover.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
