FT  27 FEB 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Pleasing durable goods orders
help to lift Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices climbed to set a record Dow high yesterday, buoyed by a
bigger than expected rise in January durable goods orders, positive comments
about lower interest rates from the US Treasury Secretary and a sharp fall
in bond yields, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 25.49 at 3,283.32,
slightly above the previous all-time peak. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 climbed
4.90 to 415.35, while the Nasdaq composite of over-the-counter stocks, which
has taken a beating from profit-takers in recent sessions, roared back with
a gain of 11.00 to 632.40. Turnover on the New York SE was heavy at 241m
shares.
The morning report that durable goods orders rose 1.5 per cent in January
provided a firm foundation for the market at the opening. Analysts had
forecast an increase of only 1 per cent. Although the difference was not
huge, any sign of economic progress is eagerly welcomed by the market in its
current uncertain mood.
Comments from Mr Nicholas Brady, the treasury secretary, that real interest
rates should be lower aided sentiment, as did a sharp cut in bond yields.
Wal-Mart advanced Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 53 7/8 after the world's biggest
retailer announced a 34 per cent increase in sales and a 25 per cent rise in
profits to Dollars 1.6bn in 1991.
ITT jumped Dollars 5 to Dollars 65 in turnover of 1.8m shares in the wake of
a Financial Times report that included hints from the chairman about
possible strategic moves by the company.
Glenfed dropped Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 7 1/8 in heavy trading after the
Florida-based savings and insurance group restated its fiscal second-quarter
profits downwards and warned that its third-quarter profitability was in
question.
Harley-Davidson rose Dollars 4 3/4 to Dollars 56 1/2 after Ms Jill Krutick,
analyst at Salomon Brothers, the securities house, raised her rating on the
stock to 'outperform'. The upgrade follows a recent meeting between analysts
and the company, which persuaded the analyst that capacity problems at the
motorcycle maker would soon be sorted out, leading to earnings for the year
that should exceed market estimates.
Telefonos de Mexico, one of the biggest stars of 1991, gained Dollars 3 1/8
to Dollars 57 7/8 after the recently privatised Mexican telecommunications
giant said that net income last year rose by almost 80 per cent.
There was strong demand for the initial public offering of Dollars 16m of
shares in Musicland Stores. Floated at Dollars 14 1/2 , it closed at Dollars
16 on 4.18m traded.
On the over-the-counter market, Microsoft forged ahead Dollars 6 1/4 to
Dollars 122 in active trading after Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, the
broking house, reinstated its 'buy' recommendation on the stock.
Amgen climbed Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 66 5/8 on news that the company will
repurchase up to Dollars 50m of its own common stock.
Autotrol plunged Dollars 5 1/4 to Dollars 9 1/2 after the company, which
manufactures water treatment control systems, announced that talks leading
to a possible takeover by the utility group Wicor (up Dollars  1/2 at
Dollars 25 7/8 ) had been terminated.
Canada
TORONTO recorded its sharpest gain since mid-January after Tuesday's release
of the Federal Budget relinquished pent-up demand. Better than expected
results from two leading Canadian banks helped the banking sector score the
largest advance.
Hefty gains in the US and Canadian bond markets, after US Federal Reserve
chairman Mr Alan Greenspan said long-term rates are too high, lent support
to the stock market.
The composite index ended 35.5 up at 3,580.5. Rises led declines by 352 to
234 after volume of 26.8m shares.
