<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Smiths poised for US avionics deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SINGAPORE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SMITHS Industries, the UK defence and aerospace components group, is about
to sign a partnership agreement with the Collins Avionics division of
Rockwell International of the US.
The venture will create a third force in the commercial aircraft avionics
sector competing against Honeywell, the market leader, and the French
Sextant avionics group.
It will also rationalise the commercial aircraft avionics business along the
same lines as the other main sectors of the commercial aerospace industry
dominated by three airframe manufacturers (Boeing, Airbus and McDonnell
Douglas) and three engine makers (Pratt &amp; Whitney, General Electric and
Rolls-Royce).
Mr Graham Thornton, marketing director of Smiths Industries' defence and
aerospace activities, said yesterday agreement between the two companies was
close. He said there was only room in the market for three groups to provide
the avionic systems for the flight decks of commercial airliners.
The venture is not expected to involve a cross-equity agreement at this
stage.
The agreement is expected to form a joint marketing company with the two
groups retaining their design and manufacturing activities. The two
companies will bid as a partnership for future avionics contracts on
airliner projects.
The partnership is also expected to focus on winning business on US Boeing
aircraft which make up about 55 per cent of the world airliner market.
Honeywell, the biggest US avionics supplier with about 35 per cent of the
world market, is dominant on McDonnell Douglas aircraft.
The French Sextant group, formed by the merger of Aerospatiale's and Thomson
CSF's avionics interests to rationalise this sector of the French
state-controlled aerospace industry, is the main avionics supplier of
European Airbus airliners.
The idea of the partnership followed an earlier unsuccessful attempt by the
two companies to bid jointly for the aircraft information management system
(AIMS) of Boeing's new 777 widebody airliner two years ago.
Although the AIMS contract was ultimately won by Honeywell, Smiths
Industries and Collins felt there were strong synergies between the two
companies and decided to discuss a broader alliance, Mr Thornton said.
</TEXT>
