<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / The Lex Column: A costly year at Barclays
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,565 (+18.2)
It is just as well that South Africa has regained some international
respectability. Otherwise Barclays Bank would not have been able to release
a full Pounds 100m of South African provisions, and its pre-tax profits
would have fallen by even more than the reported 30 per cent to Pounds 533m.
Even with that sort of flattery, however, there is no disguising a dismal
underlying performance. It has produced operating income of Pounds 2.03bn -
only Pounds 6m more than that of National Westminster - even though total
assets are 13 per cent higher.
This would matter less if Barclays' steeply rising overheads really were
largely the product of investment spending for the future. Strip out the
Pounds 90m of extra costs from the acquisitions in France and Germany and
around Pounds 45m of restructuring charges (which are carried as an
exceptional by NatWest), and overall costs still rose by 10 per cent. That
suggests some pretty deep-rooted pressures which will be hard for a
juggernaut like Barclays to slow.
Unlike National Westminster, Barclays cannot expect to benefit from falling
provisions this year. If anything its UK provisions of Pounds 1.31bn look a
little on the low side. Certainly they will be high again this year. It is
thus not surprising that its shares fell 5 per cent to 374p. The chances are
that the bank will have little scope for increasing its dividend in 1992. In
profit terms its recovery potential looks the least attractive of the three
large clearers which have reported to date.
</TEXT>
