FT  27 FEB 92 / Observer: Public affairs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Graham Mather, general director of the Institute of Economic Affairs, has
found a novel way of rebuffing those who accuse him of getting too cosy with
the Tory party. He will today host a joint seminar at the Cafe Royal with
Demos, a new left-leaning think-tank, on the future relationship between the
public and private sectors. Demos, to be formally launched in the autumn,
unites a diverse group of movers and shakers who say they are fed up with
