<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Wistful sign-off for SDP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'WHAT Social Democrats have always said is that people are much more
important than politics,' Mr John Cartwright, Social Democrat MP for
Woolwich, concluded yesterday in a faintly wistful party political broadcast
last night.
Appropriately, it is only if their constituents share that 'people rather
than politics' attitude that Mr Cartwright and Mrs Rosie Barnes, the Social
Democrat MP for neighbouring Greenwich, stand any chance of re-election.
The precedents for MPs prospering without parties are not encouraging.
The SDP itself was broken in the mould of British politics, formally winding
itself up in June 1990. Its survivors, however, remain entitled to a
broadcast on the basis of the party's performance in the 1987 election.
The product of one day's facilities from the BBC and the assistance of Mr
Mike Thomas, a former SDP MP, this final appeal to the common sense of the
ordinary voter came poignantly five years almost to the day after Mrs
Barnes' by-election victory in Greenwich.
But because it is not an election broadcast, it could not urge people
explicitly to vote for the two MPs, nor even say where they are standing.
Instead, Mr Cartwright said it was made 'because we want to make it clear to
people that the ideas of social democracy are still there, still alive, and
they're still extremely relevant to Britain at the present point.'
In a quick-fire duet on the SDP's approach, the two MPs offered a serving of
the party's familiar brand of compassion and efficiency.
Of its most famous incarnation, Dr David Owen, the party's former leader who
is standing down at the election, there was no mention.
He had used a party broadcast during the Liberal Democrat conference last
autumn to call for an anti-federalist crusade.
Mr Cartwright concluded: 'A handful of Social Democrats in the House of
Commons would clearly be part of that bridgehead for common sense which most
people want to see between the two big parties.'
With just two candidates, both of whom are defending majorities of about
2,000 in London constituencies against strong Labour challenges, belief in
their ability to achieve even this is hard to square with the classic SDP
mix of heart and head.
</TEXT>
