<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Kinnock says party 'ready to win' -
Labour National Executive Committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR leadership yesterday defied the government to call off an April 9
general election, claiming the voters' would not forgive the Tories if they
failed to announce the ballot by the end of Budget week - a fateful Friday
March 13.
In an upbeat farewell to his national executive committee at what Labour is
certain was its last meeting before a poll, Mr Neil Kinnock claimed that the
party had never been more prepared for an election.
He went on to warn that any postponement of the election would be read by
voters as evidence of the desperation of a government that had run out of
ideas.
In a rallying call as much for the media as his colleagues, the Labour
leader told the executive: 'We are ready to run, ready to win and ready to
serve.'
Mr Larry Whitty, the party's general secretary, reiterated the warning that
the Tories would damage themselves if they delayed until later in the year.
Mr David Hill, Labour's communications director, added that in the event of
a postponment the whole focus of the pre-election campaign would switch to
the reasons behind the delay.
In the interim, Labour is planning to convene its specially constituted
joint shadow cabinet-executive group, known as the Clause Five committee,
immediately after the dissolution to approve the manifesto. The document
will then be published within the first week of the campaign.
The party's parliamentary planners are expected not to attempt to disrupt
the Budget, preferring instead to use the televised proceedings of
parliament to make its case for public expenditure in place of tax cuts.
Labour's own detailed tax and spending proposals, including a decision on
whether the removal of the ceiling on national insurance contributions will
be phased in or done at once, will only be revealed in the week after the
Budget.
An aide to Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, said Labour would need some
time to analyse the Budget figures and did not want to make its announcement
when press attention was focused on rallies launching the start of the
election campaign proper.
Party officials expressed confidence that when the real campaign does get
under way, the pressure will be on Mr John Major, the prime minister, and
not Mr Kinnock whose greater experience on the hustings as a party leader
would give him a natural advantage.
The executive cleared the decks of party business yesterday by approving
candidates, recently elected by local parties, to contest a number of
hitherto vacant seats.
They included candidates for Wallasey and Nottingham East and replacements
for Mr Terry Fields, MP for Liverpool Broadgreen, and Mr Dave Nellist, MP
for Coventry South East, who were expelled from the party for their alleged
links with the proscribed Militant group.
</TEXT>
