FT  27 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Supergun report 'before election' -
Trade And Industry Committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR protested yesterday that the government was blocking a Commons'
investigation into the Iraqi supergun affair by telling witnesses they need
not answer all MPs questions.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow trade and industry secretary, wrote to the prime
minister complaining about the advice given to some witnesses by the office
of Mr John MacGregor, leader of the Commons.
Earlier, the cross-party trade and industry committee promised to report its
findings on the affair ahead of the general election.
Mr Kenneth Warren, Tory chairman of the committee, announced its decision
after some members had voiced fears that they would be unable to publish
their findings because of a lack of parliamentary time.
The committee, which has been investigating the affair for several months,
plans to publish a report before the dissolution of parliament. Mr Alan
Clark, the defence minister, and Mr Tim Sainsbury, the trade minister are
due to give evidence at the committee's final session today.
Downing Street Officials rejected Mr Brown's comments, saying some witnesses
had asked for guidance but had not been told what to do.
The committee accused Customs and Excise yesterday of hiding behind advice
by Sir Patrick Mayhew, attorney-general, when it refused to discuss evidence
in the supergun case.
Sir Patrick told the committee that his endorsement of the decision was made
under a convention observed with Customs and Excise although it was not
under his jurisdiction. He denied that Customs was hiding behind his advice.
Sir Brian Unwin, Customs and Excise chairman, confirmed it was his decision
to drop prosecutions in the case after the attorney-general had been
consulted. When pressed by MPs he refused to give details about evidence
that led to the decision.
