<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Parliament and Politics: Beith warning on minority rule -
Liberal Democrats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL Democrats have stepped up their attempts to force a coalition
government in the event of a hung parliament by warning of the economic
damage a minority government would inflict on Britain.
Mr Alan Beith, Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman, yesterday said a Labour
or Tory government, unable to command a parliamentary majority and
struggling to survive before calling a second general election, was 'a
recipe for economic chaos and damage'.
A coalition government, with an agreed programme of government, could help
stabilise prices, Mr Beith said. During the pact between the Liberal and
Labour parties in 1977-78, inflation fell from 21 per cent to 7 per cent, he
added.
Liberal Democrats know the two main parties will not willingly agree a
post-election deal - largely because of insistence on electoral reform as a
pre-condition for support. So they are anxious to increase the moral
pressure on Labour and the Tories to form a coalition.
The party has been encouraged by a report by UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, the
securities house, which said that the worst outcome of the election would be
'a lame minority government which, eschewing formal pacts, limped along in a
policy vacuum'.
P &amp; D praised the Liberal Democrat economic policies as the 'most logically
argued and the most sensibly radical'.
It added: 'For economic performance, the better outcome would involve power
sharing in which the Liberal Democrats pressed home their economic programme
 -bringing out the best features of the Conservatives' policies or limiting
the possible damage of Labour's'
The Liberal Democrats will emphasise at a defence policy launch today that
their past target of a 50 per cent cut in defence spending by 2000 is only
an aspiration, and depends on a thorough review of the UK's defence needs.
</TEXT>
