<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / UK News (Employment): TUC estimates membership is down by
only 5 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEMBERSHIP of unions affiliated to the Trades Union Congress fell by between
5 per cent and 5.5 per cent last year, according to a confidential survey
carried out by Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary.
The estimate, disclosed to members of the TUC general council yesterday,
suggests that the recession has had a less serious impact on membership than
was previously believed.
Nonetheless the decline, and continued losses expected this year, was severe
enough to persuade the general council to agree proposals for a 20 per cent
cut in the TUC wage bill and a rationalisation of departments. A reduction
of 5 per cent to 5.5 per cent in 1991 would be similar to the fall of 1990
when membership fell from 8.65m to 8.19m. It would mean a further reduction
of 400,000 members to about 7.8m. That compares with 12.12m in 1979.
Two unions - the AEU engineers and the FTAT furniture workers' union - have
recently reported a 10 per cent decline in membership. Some public service
unions, however, including Nalgo, have in-creased membership.
The general council was told that without remedial action the 5 per cent
decline would lead to a loss of Pounds 250,000 this year and Pounds 1m next.
Mr Willis won support for a 20 per cent cut in the wage bill, or Pounds 1m
in the full year, with changes in top staff posts and a cut in the number of
departments and regional offices.
The TUC superannuation management committee has already agreed an early
retirement package for people aged 50 and over. It also has plans for a
Pounds 500,000 voluntary severance scheme that would provide one month's pay
for each year of service.
</TEXT>
