<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / National Institute Economic Review: Further 300,000 job
losses forecast by 1994
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK faces more than 300,000 further job losses in the next 22 months, the
National Institute of Economic and Social Research says.
The institute, a leading economic think-tank, forecasts in its quarterly
review published yesterday that the jobless total will increase to 2.92m by
the end of next year and stay around 2m for the rest of the decade.
A more cheerful conclusion is that a limited recovery from the recession is
likely in the second half of this year, with gross domestic product set to
increase 1.3 per cent after a 2.6 per cent fall last year. The institute
expects growth of 2.7 per cent next year.
In its assessment of options in the March 10 Budget the institute advises Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to put a boost for investment ahead of
proposals to cut income tax.
Support for companies' capital-spending plans would help UK productivity to
catch up with levels overseas. A tax cut would act mainly to stimulate
consumer spending, which the institute says would be 'not ideal' as a method
of speeding up the recovery.
The economic revival is likely to be held back by a further fall in
investment this year, and by an upturn in the housing market that will be
limited.
The institute believes Mr Lamont will inject Pounds 2bn into the economy by
taking 1p off the standard income-tax rate. A stimulus of this kind would
push the public sector borrowing requirement to Pounds 22.2bn in 1992-93,
and Pounds 21.6bn the following year. In both cases this amounts to about
3.5 per cent of gross domestic product.
The institute warns that any effort beyond such a relatively modest cut in
personal taxation to boost spending by consumers could increase inflation.
In spite of a slowdown in the past year, inflation is still not 'safely in
line' with levels in France and Germany. As a result 'Britain cannot afford
a really rapid recovery'.
The institute says the retail prices index will continue to show only small
year-on-year changes for some time. It reckons this will be 3.4 per cent at
the end of this year and 3.5 per cent at the end of next year.
Among the main factors increasing UK growth this year will be the Pounds
11bn additional pubic spending for 1992-93 announced by the Treasury last
November. The UK's ability to use fiscal policy to stimulate the economy
will be limited, however, by the need to keep sterling in its band in the
European exchange rate mechanism. That will restrict annual growth and keep
unemployment high.
The institute reckons the jobless total will climb to 2.83m by the end of
this year from 2.6m in January. The figure has risen by about 1m since March
1990.
The institute hints that the UK monetary authorities should take action to
damp erratic movements in credit to consumers and industry. Loans to these
groups jumped in the mid to late 1980s, fuelling the 1986-88 boom, and have
contracted sharply during the recession.
'A more cautious lending policy by the banking system can be expected in the
light of recent experiences - and should be welcomed as more conducive to
macroeconomic stability,' it says.
Exports are expected to grow by 2.8 per cent this year compared with 1 per
cent in 1991, helping the UK's growth prospects. The good performance by
exporters may be partly because of a recovery in world trade, which is
likely to grow by 4.4 per cent this year after 1.1 per cent last year.
Any larger increase in world trade will be prevented by relatively slow
expansion in the world economy. Growth in gross domestic product in the
seven biggest industrialised economies - the US, Japan, Germany, Italy,
France, Canada and Britain - will be 1.9 per cent in this year, after 0.9
per cent last year and 2.4 per cent in 1990.
Economic Review No 139. NIESR, 2 Dean Trench Street, Smith Square, London
SW1P 3HE. By subscription.
</TEXT>
