<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Rival to BT and Mercury seeks licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL NETWORK, the private UK telecommunications operator, has applied
for a full international and domestic telecommunications licence in
competition with BT and Mercury Communications.
The group, which offers a telephone service over the Post Office's internal
network, is one of about 20 companies which have lodged licence applications
with the Department of Trade and Industry following last year's white paper
liberalising the market.
The variety of services the applicants propose to provide seems to support
the government's contention that its policy has unleashed innovation. Apart
from National Network and a similar application from Sprint, the US group,
applicants are avoiding a head-on clash with BT and Mercury and focusing on
niche markets instead.
Mr Michael Davies, National Network's chairman and majority shareholder,
said the DTI was in 'a very advanced stage of drafting' his company's
domestic licence.
The application for an international licence is likely to be more
controversial, as the government has made clear that it is not encouraging
full international network competition with BT and Mercury at this stage.
Similar considerations are holding up Sprint's international licence
application.
Mr Davies said National Network planned to form strategic alliances with
other groups to raise funds to build a network. Initially it would
concentrate on business customers, linking their premises to a backbone
national network with microwave or other radio links.
The government has recently awarded licences to British Aerospace
Communications and US-based Alpha Lyracom to provide international satellite
services; to Ionica, a private UK group, to provide residential phone
services over radio links; and to four groups to supply data communications
services by radio.
Other companies which have applied for licences include Millicom, World
Communications and ACC, all of which are north American groups.
</TEXT>
