<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Scargill allegation is denied
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL yesterday denied allegations by the National Union of
Mineworkers that it was planning to suspend payments into its pension fund.
Mr Arthur Scargill, president of the union, said the money saved from such a
'holiday' would make British Coal's accounts look artificially good.
He said in a letter to Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the Commons social
security committee, that he believed British Coal would use the large
surplus in its pension fund to pay for a 'holiday', during which it would
make no more contributions to miners' pensions.
Mr Scargill added that British Coal had taken such a 'holiday' in 1989.
According to Mr Scargill the fund now has an actuarial surplus of Pounds
1,450m.
He told Mr Field: 'We have now been informed that British Coal is insisting
on a substantial slice of this surplus in the form of another contribution
holiday.
'If it is allowed to take it, this means that British Coal will have paid no
contributions at all over the 10-year period from 1989 to 1999, while miners
continue to pay their contributions.'
British Coal said it had not yet received the actuarial report on the
miners' pension fund. It had not decided how any surplus should be used.
The European Commission has approved a Pounds 124.2m aid package for
Britain's coal-mining areas. The package had been blocked by the commission
pending government guarantees that the cash was being properly used.
</TEXT>
