FT  27 FEB 92 / Legal aid awarded to Ramsden
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TERRY RAMSDEN, former chairman of Glen International, an investment firm
which collapsed in 1987 with losses of Pounds 142m, has been granted legal
aid for his defence against criminal charges.
City of London magistrates yesterday said a contribution by Mr Ramsden of
Pounds 25,000, assessed by the court's legal aid officer, would not become
payable until the end of the criminal proceedings.
Mr Ramsden was remanded on Pounds 150,000 bail until April 29. Mr Michael
Drury, for the Serious Fraud Office, told the magistrates that by this time
proceedings for transfer of the case to the crown court would have taken
place. The magistrates altered Mr Ramsden's bail conditions to allow him to
report to Fulham police once a week instead of daily.
A condition that he must have no contact with a list of people was amended
to permit contact through his solicitors.
It was Mr Ramsden's second court appearance since his voluntary return to
the UK two weeks ago after waiving his right to contest proceedings for his
extradition from the US.
The 22 charges against him include allegations of fraudulent trading,
obtaining property by deception, dishonestly inducing creditors to wait for
payment, false accounting and making deceptive statements to investors.
