<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Fear of action by Labour prompted scrapping of coal terminal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS that a Labour government would ban or limit coal imports to protect
British Coal prompted PowerGen, the electricity generator, to seek the delay
in developing Britain's biggest coal terminal which led to the unexpected
cancellation of the project.
The terminal, at Immingham on the Humber, would have been capable of
handling 12m tonnes of foreign coal a year, threatening the jobs of miners
in the Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire coalfields.
Associated British Ports (ABP), which was leading the project, said it had
cancelled the scheme because PowerGen had already delayed for too long. The
other partner in the project was the generator National Power.
PowerGen said the project's collapse opened the way for British Coal to
compete with imports and offer the electricity industry cheap coal. 'In
their own hands lies the future of British pits and miners' jobs,' said Mr
Ed Wallis, PowerGen's chief executive.
He said he was surprised by ABP's 'precipitous' decision, but believed
PowerGen had made the right choice in holding back until after the election.
'We took a totally commercial view. If we couldn't put coal through the
terminal, we would have been wasting shareholders' money.'
Labour could restrict coal imports, under the EC's coal and steel treaty
which overrides other EC legislation.
Mr Wallis played down the importance of the Immingham project, which he said
was far less attractive to the two generators than other projects at
Bristol, Liverpool, Hull and on Teesside. 'We are in a very strong
position,' he said. 'We only want to burn 19m tonnes of imports, and we can
already import half of that with existing projects.'
PowerGen was unlikely to commit itself to another coal terminal project
before the election, he said, but he insisted that it would not pay the
existing premium of Pounds 20 per tonne for UK coal. If British Coal prices
did not fall, it would seek alternative supplies.
Mr Neil Clarke, British Coal chairman, said the cancellation of Immingham
was encouraging for the corporation. But the UK's rush to invest in
gas-fired power stations was a much more serious threat to the company than
coal imports.
</TEXT>
