<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / US leads the charge as allies fight for Kuwaiti contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON, Middle East Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TO THE victors go the spoils of war: at least, this was the hope of US,
British and French companies which rushed to liberated Kuwait last year for
shares of what promised to be a Dollars 100bn (Pounds 57bn) harvest of
rebuilding contracts.
A year on, though, it is clear that the rebuilding bill will be only about a
fifth of the earliest estimates. It also appears that companies from only
one of the Gulf war allies, the US, is winning anything like victors'
spoils.
'We're doing well,' said one US official. 'Kuwait is certainly favouring US
companies.'
US groups have won at least Dollars 2bn worth of contracts and export orders
in Kuwait since last March. Moreover, US exporters have increased market
share in Kuwait, notably for cars and foods. Officials expect pre-war export
levels of around Dollars 800m a year will rise to average more than Dollars
1bn for the next few years.
US companies should also do well out of contracts still to be let. Of a
likely bill for reconstruction of around Dollars 20bn over the next two or
three years, at least half will be spent on restoring the oil industry,
while this year's budget set aside Dollars 9bn for defence spending. US
groups are leading contenders in both fields.
Bechtel, the private Californian group, has been in Kuwait since liberation
with an open-ended deal as the services contractor for restoring the oil
industry. No one will put a figure on the deal, but it is certain to be
worth hundreds of millions of dollars.
Three US groups, Brown &amp; Root, Fluor Daniel and Foster Wheeler, are also the
leading contenders to win the management contract for repairing Kuwait's
three oil refineries - a task expected to cost Dollars 2bn overall. 'We're
pretty optimistic it will go our way,' said a US diplomat.
In defence, the US is already providing the first of 40 F-18 jets under a
Dollars 1.6bn deal signed in 1988. It also has an Dollars 81m agreement
under which two US groups have begun Dollars 42.5m worth of work repairing
the country's two air bases. Kuwait is also considering buying up to 200
Abrams M1A2 tanks.
AT &amp; T is fighting hard to enter Kuwait's telecommunications market, largely
at the expense of Ericsson of Sweden, which built most of the existing
network. The US company hopes to win contracts worth up to Dollars 200m.
British and, particularly, French officials are disappointed. 'The overall
picture here of awarding contracts is gloomy,' said a French diplomat, who
reckoned French groups had tendered for Dollars 1.5bn worth of contracts but
won just Dollars 500m worth since liberation. Most of this represents the
French share of Kuwait's postwar Dollars 2bn order for 15 Airbus airliners.
However, General Electric of the US is involved in the supply of the Airbus'
engines (through CFM, a joint venture with France's Snecma) while Boeing is
to supply three 747 jets.
French officials are also piqued that none of their bidders won any
significant share of the effort to control Kuwait's oil fires or of
subsequent oilfield recovery work - a situation they attribute to lobbying
by Bechtel.
British companies have fared slightly better. Officials in Kuwait estimate
that the UK has won nearly Dollars 1bn of trade and contracts since
liberation, though this includes a Dollars 200m share of the Airbus
contract.
Among the main British successes, the Kuwait British Group, a consortium of
Wimpey, AMEC and Taylor Woodrow has a contract worth nearly Dollars 200m to
restore output from the northern oilfields; Morrison has secured Dollars 40m
worth of work repairing the water system; and Royal Ordnance, a subsidiary
of British Aerospace, has mine and ordnance clearance contracts worth around
Dollars 100m.
Britain's main hope for further large contracts lies in defence, where the
Challenger 2 tank is competing against the US Abrams. But UK officials say
few other big contracts appear likely to go Britain's way, and Kuwait's
appeal to contractors has suffered accordingly. 'The level of interest in
this market shown by British companies has just dropped off,' said a UK
official.
