<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / IAEA acts to tighten checks for N-weapons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Atomic Energy Agency is to extend its powers to check for
clandestine nuclear weapons development, including inspection of undeclared
sites and gathering foreign intelligence.
The new measures agreed in Vienna yesterday by the policy-making board of
the IAEA, the United Nations nuclear watchdog, amount to a fairly modest
tightening of safeguards against nuclear proliferation. Critics say the IAEA
needs much stronger powers if it is to avoid repeating its failure to detect
Iraq's secret development of a nuclear bomb.
The 35-nation board affirmed the right of its 200 inspectors to visit any
site they chose in countries which have signed the agency's safeguards
agreements. They will also be able to consult foreign intelligence sources
for clues about secret weapons projects.
The board also agreed that member states should submit in advance any design
for new installations or changes to existing nuclear sites.
'The board further reaffirmed the agency's rights to obtain and have access
to additional information and locations,' Mr Hans Blix, IAEA
director-general, said.
But a proposal to compile a central IAEA database of imports and exports of
sensitive equipment and nuclear materials was not accepted. Several western
industrialised countries said the information would be too laborious and
costly to collect.
'The intention is to build up a picture of who is importing equipment that
is incongruous with the scale of its known nuclear programme,' said Mr David
Kyd, IAEA information director. 'It will mean a lot of work but unless
someone does this, it is going to be a critical weakness in the system.'
IAEA officials said the tightening of controls would only apply to members
which had signed full safeguards agreements. Countries with agreements to
inspect only specific reactors, such as Algeria, would not be obliged to
open other sites for inspection.
The next IAEA board meeting in June will resume the discussion of stronger
safeguards, including the proposed database of materials and equipment. It
will also have to tackle the impending financial crisis, following the loss
of the Soviet Union's contribution to the agency. The IAEA's Dollars 75m a
year inspection budget has been cut by 18 per cent at a time when its
existing workload is increasing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
