<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / Fraud law faces urgent reform in England
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is considering remodelling key aspects of English fraud law
along Scottish lines as part of an urgent reform package to solve the
problems of complex and unmanageable City trials.
This follows widespread criticism of the handling of high profile trials
such as Guinness, Blue Arrow and Barlow Clowes which reached their
conclusions after many years of costly wrangling.
The main reform under consideration is the introduction of a wide-ranging
offence of fraud which does not exist under present English law.
In Scotland, a charge of fraud may be brought under common law and does not
need to be allied to a particular statute as it does in England.
However, thoughts of abandoning trial by jury in complex fraud cases, as
recommended by the report of the Roskill Fraud Trials Committee, are not
being seriously entertained.
The government may also enact measures to shorten the length of trials by
ensuring that arguments outlined by defendants at pre-trial reviews are
adhered to when they reach full trials.
The government has been under extreme pressure in recent weeks to come up
with a cheaper and quicker way of dealing with serious fraud.
The collapse two weeks ago of the second trial arising out of the 1986
Guinness takeover of Distillers was accompanied by a call from the presiding
judge for a 'radical solution' to the problems of long fraud cases.
The absence of a simple fraud charge means that prosecuting authorities such
as the Serious Fraud Office have to identify specific acts such as
fraudulent trading, misuse of company funds or false accounting.
The indictment in the Blue Arrow trial, which lasted just over a year and
cost an estimated Pounds 35m, contained only one charge but was followed by
20 paragraphs of detailed allegations, each of which had to be explained to
the jury. Government law officers will need to find a way of framing a
simple charge of fraud without having to include complicated and costly
specific allegations similar to those in the Blue Arrow indictment to cover
the particular circumstances of each case.
Mr Justice Henry, the judge in all four Guinness trials, told the jury:
'Once again this case has thrown up the problems of long criminal trials and
the appropriateness of our criminal justice system . . . to such long and
complex trials.'
Mr John Redwood, corporate affairs minister, recently undertook to consider
any request from the SFO to allow it to opt for civil instead of criminal
proceedings in prosecuting large fraud cases.
In civil cases, prosecuting authorities need to establish their case only on
a 'balance of probabilities', rather than the more stringent 'beyond
reasonable doubt' criterion required in criminal cases.
Mr Redwood also agreed to look at any SFO request for greater investigative
powers.
A move to increase the effectiveness of pre-trial reviews would probably
chime well with the views of Lord Roskill, who chaired the three-year
inquiry into the conduct of fraud cases which reported in 1986.
The former Law Lord argued earlier this month that 'a very firm line' should
be taken at preliminary hearings 'so that the issues have been streamlined
by the time the case gets to trial.'
The Labour party has said it would streamline the role of agencies
responsible for dealing with fraud and would consider appointing specialist
legal advisers to juries involved in complex cases.
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, acknowledged two weeks ago that urgent
attention needed to be given to possible changes, while warning there was no
easy solution.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
