<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / International Company News: Alcan forecasts continued
oversupply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALCAN Aluminium says oversupply of metal will persist this year despite a
slowdown in exports from the former east bloc to the west in the first two
months.
Alcan is maintaining its quarterly dividend of 15 US cents but expects
another tough year, says Mr David Morton, chairman.
The Canadian company has pared capital outlays to USDollars 550m from
USDollars 880m in 1991 and the investment will be confined to completing
rolling mill capacity in the US and Germany. However, Alcan will keep
environmental spending up to USDollars 120m.
Mr Jacques Bougie, president, said Alcan will cut another USDollars 300m
from its cost base in 1992 and more in 1993. Productivity targets throughout
its bauxite, alumina, smelting and fabricating operations worldwide are now
set in a five-year time frame.
He said that although recent spot market prices reflected the slowdown in
the flow of east European metals to the west, Alcan was being extremely
cautious and suspects the inflow will resume soon due to foreign exchange
pressures.
Alcan has stopped work on the Kemano hydro-electric project in northern
British Columbia, required for the expansion of its smelter nearby,
following a court judgment on environmental issues now under appeal.
In 1991, Alcan posted a loss of USDollars 36m, or 25 cents a share, against
a profit of USDollars 543m, or Dollars 2.33, in 1990. Revenues were
USDollars 7.75bn against USDollars 8.7bn.
</TEXT>
