FT  27 FEB 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Presumably the only people not cheering on Richard Branson in his fight to
break into the air travel business are those employed by other airlines.
Faced with such wickedly high prices, especially in Europe, the rest of us
would be only too glad to see him succeed against the cartel. This Week
(8.30 ITV) considers Virgin's latest efforts, directed at the South African
route, and consults one of Branson's predecessors in the cartel-busting
business, Freddy Laker. His advice is straightforward: 'Sue the bastards'.
Switch to Channel 4 when that ends and you will find television's beady eye
fixed upon another example of big business taking the small man to the
cleaners: The Barlow Clowes Affair.
A fresh batch of the Western series Paradise (11.20 BBC1) begins with the
supposedly retired gunfighter Ethan Cord tangling with a corrupt lawman to
prevent the hanging of a Texas Ranger who once saved his life. Since
television Westerns are now as rare as dragon's teeth it is a pity this one
is not better. Oddly enough, BBC2 begins the evening with Bonanza: The Next
Generation (6.00) which should irritate 'Bonanza' fans since it stars none
of the familiar cast.
