<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / London's voluntary groups see funds fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITY financial support for London's voluntary sector has declined
at a time of escalating need, research conducted for the capital's statutory
grant-making body has concluded.
A survey of 27 of the 33 London borough councils showed funding for
voluntary groups fell from Pounds 141m in 1990-91 to Pounds 127m in 1991-92.
Only seven boroughs maintained their financial support in real terms. In
inner London - where many of the capital's social problems are concentrated
 -reductions in spending were more than twice as great as in outer boroughs.
The research was conducted by the London Chamber of Commerce and Industry on
behalf of the London Boroughs Grants Committee, which makes grants to
voluntary organisations operating in more than one borough.
Mr Serge Lourie, a Liberal Democrat councillor who chairs the committee,
said the research showed a 'critical' situation in which funding could not
keep up with needs.
He said: 'Our concern is that the disintegration of our social fabric
threatens London's future prosperity.'
The research is the latest in a series of studies showing that, in spite of
government pressure for voluntary organisations to take on additional
duties, the sector's financial difficulties are worsening. The London
chamber believes demand for voluntary organisations' services will continue
to grow, while the financial climate in which they operate is unlikely to
improve.
The chamber's report said: 'Continued and perhaps increased restrictions on
local authority spending will squeeze resources at borough and London
Boroughs Grants Committee level, while recession will reduce the amount of
private sector money available.'
It argued that the voluntary sector's contribution to the vitality and
prosperity of London 'needs to be recognised at the highest levels of
business and government'. The 'dramatic reductions' in local authority
funding raised the need for improved efficiency in the use of existing
resources, but this did not negate the need for greater financial input from
both the public and private sectors.
</TEXT>
