<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / National Institute Economic Review: Motor parts industry
lags far behind Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRODUCTIVITY gap between the UK and German vehicle components industries
narrowed in the 1980s according to the National Institute.
The report says both countries still lag far behind the productivity of
Japanese suppliers.
In the 1980s, UK components suppliers 'finally dealt with blatant
under-utilisation of capital equipment, but this has not proved to be
enough'.
The report highlights deficiencies in UK training and education as
underlying causes for low productivity.
Mr Christopher Carr, senior fellow in strategic management at Manchester
Business School, the author of the report, says that if the remaining gap
between the UK and German industries is to be bridged, 'the 1990s needs to
become the decade in which Britain grapples with similarly blatant
under-utilisation of people's full career potentials'.
The report says that 'the critical conclusion, however, is that while
Britain may still have some lessons to learn from Germany in respect to
manufacturing productivity, the much larger and still continuing gap is
against Japan'.
According to one battery maker, 'while the most efficient battery plants in
western Europe were now generally up to six or seven batteries per man
hour,' the Japanese were producing more than 10.'
</TEXT>
