<HEADLINE>
FT  27 FEB 92 / BTR chief defends corporate leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England and the Institutional Shareholders' Committee were
'doing a disservice to investors by encouraging them to think of themselves
as owners' according to Sir Owen Green, chairman of the conglomerate BTR,
yesterday.
Speaking at the annual investment conference of the National Association of
Pension Funds in Eastbourne, he robustly attacked institutional investors'
attitudes to corporate governance.
Debating with Mr Mike Sandland, chairman of the ISC, he denounced concepts
such as audit committees and independent non-executive directors. 'The word
independence sticks in my gullet,' said Sir Owen, whose company has been one
of the most successful in Britain over the past 20 years.
'I don't think there is very much wrong with corporate governance as it
stands,' he said. There might be a problem with institutional investors
growing so large that they could not easily sell investments in companies
they did not like, but that, he said, was a fiscal problem rather than one
of corporate governance.
Mr Sandland, an investment manager with Norwich Union, said shareholders
should assume the responsibilities of ownership. Institutional investors
should show their commitment by registering votes and playing a full role as
active shareholders.
Sir Owen said shareholders would be better regarded as freeholder landlords
than owners of public companies. 'It is different in concept from the
ownership of goods and chattels,' he insisted.
In one respect, however, Sir Owen supported in principle a recent
pronouncement of the ISC, which represents the view of various kinds of
institutions including pension funds. He agreed that the chairman of a
company should not be the chief executive as well.
Even here, however, he suggested that the ISC had 'copped out'. Too many
important people had influenced the ISC, which continued reluctantly to
accept the combination of the two roles subject to safeguards and
conditions. 'It ought to be stopped tomorrow,' Sir Owen said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
