<TEXT>
MR Manfred Worner, Nato secretary-general, yesterday said he regretted that
Canada had decided to bring home its troops from Europe, signalling alliance
concern about the weakening of crucial transatlantic links, Reuter reports.
Canada's government announced the decision on Tuesday as part of cuts to
pull the country out of recession.
'While I recognise the financial pressures which led to this decision, I
have noted it with considerable regret, given the political and military
importance of the presence of Canadian forces in Europe,' Mr Worner said.
Britain yesterday also expressed concern at the Canadian move. 'The decision
to withdraw the remaining Canadian forces is a sad end to a long and valued
Canadian deployment in West Europe,' the Foreign Office said. 'We note that
the withdrawal will be phased over two to three years and we hope that this
may give time (for Canada) to reconsider.'
