<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ABSENCE of any signs of reduction in UK interest rates, together with
figures showing a fall in US consumer confidence, caused a retreat in FT-SE
stock index futures after an initial jump, writes Joel Kibazo.
The March contract, having started the session at 2,579, saw light selling.
The downward trend was, however, reversed by speculation, later confirmed,
of a 0.25 per cent cut in the Bank of Spain's official intervention rate.
This triggered a squeeze in the March future, sending it to the day's high
of 2,596 as dealers anticipated that the Bank of England might soon follow
suit.
It did not, and selling followed which gathered pace with the release of
poor US consumer confidence statistics. These, in turn, led to falls on Wall
Street, once again hurting the March contract.
March finished at 2,557, around 4 points above its estimated fair value
premium to cash of about 6. Turnover reached almost 7,000 contracts.
Traded options remained dull, volume totalling 24,491 contracts, with the
FT-SE 100 index option having 8,872 lots transacted. British Airways was the
busiest stock option, with 1,744 lots dealt.
