FT  26 FEB 92 / International Company News: Review of Berlitz could lead to
sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BERLITZ, the language school subsidiary of Maxwell Communication Corporation
(MCC), said it has hired the Wall Street stockbroking firm of Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette (DLJ) to conduct a strategic review that could lead to the
sale or recapitalisation of the company.
Berlitz said DLJ would consider alternatives, including the sale of all or
part of the company. Another option would be the continued New York Stock
Exchange listing of Berlitz as an independent company.
Mr Joe Rodgers, Berlitz chairman, said the company's committee of
independent directors had decided to expand DLJ's role from a more narrow
previous assignment.
Any recommendations from DLJ will nonetheless be difficult to implement in
the near-term.
MCC, which nominally owns 56.5 per cent of Berlitz shares, is itself
operating under Chapter 11 of US bankruptcy law in a complex arrangement
that requires co-ordination between New York and UK court-appointed
administrators of the Maxwell empire.
At present, most of MCC's 56.5 per cent Berlitz stake is actually in the
hands of five US and European banks and companies that received the stock as
collateral for loans to Mr Maxwell. The pledging of the Berlitz shares was
discovered last year after MCC had announced the sale for Dollars 265m of
56.5 per cent of Berlitz to Fukutake, the Japanese publisher.
Earlier this month, Berlitz adopted a 'poison pill' scheme designed to deter
an unwanted change in the control of the company. Macmillan has meanwhile
brought injunctions against the banks that received Berlitz shares from Mr
Maxwell to prevent them from selling the stock.
